John Edwards: Language skills are vital to the world's citizens
Scotland’s independent schools have a reputation for excellence in education and have maintained this reputation in 2018, when once again outstanding exam results were achieved, further enhanced by individual and collective achievements in sports, the arts, music and other public events.
These schools, with a total of 30,000 students in Scotland and represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best level of education for their students and their parents.
Independent schools have set a goal to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen career and their life as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement specific school programmes, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desirable subject in our schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a person in a language that he understands, it remains in his consciousness.
If you speak his native language, it remains in his heart."
It is a compelling reminder that we cannot simply rely on English when we want to build relationships and gain the trust of people from other countries.
Taking into account the recent results of this year's exams, we can see that the languages are at the top of the league tables with the highest number of exams passed in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of the students who taught foreign languages reached the top grade A.
The Scottish Council of Independent Schools’ data on 74 schools shows that 72 percent of students got the highest grade in Chinese, and 72 percent of those who learned German, 69 percent of those who learned French, and 63 percent of those who learned Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now as highly valued as subjects of choice in the programmes of independent schools as those of the science-technology-engineering and mathematics group.
A 2014 survey by the UK’s Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17 percent of employers cited a lack of language skills as a reason for failing to fill vacancies.
As a result, language skills are increasingly becoming compulsory to prepare young people for future careers.
With growing job opportunities that will require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of their chosen career, learning a foreign language will be a real benefit for them in the future.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically improve the competitiveness of a multi-language speaker.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in Britain, 75 percent did not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, while French was the only language spoken by a double-digit number of people, 15 percent.
That is why investing in language teaching is important for today’s children.
Multilingualism, especially in developing countries, will give children better opportunities for meaningful work.
Schools in Scotland differ in the languages they teach.
Some schools will focus more on the more common modern languages, while others will teach languages such as Chinese and Japanese, which are considered the most important for Britain's future, according to plans for 2020.
No matter what your child is interested in, independent schools will always be able to choose from several languages, and teachers will be specialists in the field.
Scotland’s independent schools are committed to providing a language environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever their future.
At present, in the global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still vital for the future of the country, so this fact should be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be seen as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish youth this choice, diversity and excellence.
Il faut bien le faire (It must be done).
John Edwards is the Director of the Scottish Independent Schools Council
