Harvard students will learn a subject on how to relax enough
A new subject at Harvard University has made students sleep more this year, an attempt to counter the increasingly popular culture of brutalism, which involves studying caffeine over and over.
One professor found that students at the best universities in the world often did not even have a basic understanding of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed a subject he thought was the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create a new subject after talking about the effects of lack of sleep on learning.
"At the end, a girl came up to me and asked, 'Why am I only being told this now that I'm in my final year?'
She found that no one had ever explained to her how important sleep was — what surprised me, he told the Telegraph.
Launched for the first time this year, the subject provides students with a basic insight into how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sporting achievement and overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, informed that the university decided to introduce a training course after learning that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week of study.
The hour-long training process includes a series of interactive exercises.
One of the parts is an image of a dormitory door, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how performance in sports is affected by lack of sleep and the importance of bedtime routines.
In another part, students are informed about how prolonged lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Then the map of the campus with interactive icons invites participants to rethink their daily routine.
"We know that it will not change the behavior of students at once.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know how your health will be affected by cigarette smoking," added Professor Chaisler.
He said that a culture that boasts of being able to learn all night long still exists, and added that modern technology and increasing pressure on students meant that lack of sleep became an increasingly serious problem.
He explained that enough quality sleep should be the students’ “secret weapon” to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even to prevent weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into fasting mode, making it constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chaseler develop the subject after attending one of his lectures last year, Harvard’s first year.
He said that the subject had opened his eyes and inspired him to make the course accessible to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask students who are in postgraduate education to study a similar program before going to enjoy the competition.
Professor Chaisler advises students to install an alarm not only when they get up, but also when they go to sleep, and also to keep in mind how people are harmed by the "blue lights" emitted by the screens of electronic devices and LED lamps, as they can disrupt the circadian rhythms, making it difficult to fall asleep.
